<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910816-0021</DOCNO><DOCID>910816-0021.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Officer at Nikko Unit   Pleads Guilty in Loan Scam</HL><DATE>08/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   J.NKT</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)SWITZERLAND (SZ)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Mona Sun, a former vice president of NikkoSecurities Co.'s U.S. unit, pleaded guilty to six felonies inconnection with a scheme to defraud Nikko and Dreieck FinanzAG of $120 million.   Ms. Sun, fired from Nikko's New York office in January1988, pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy and fivecounts of fraud. She was extradited from Hong Kong to theU.S. earlier this year.</LP><TEXT>   Prosecutors said that in October 1987, Ms. Sun used herposition at Nikko Securities International Inc. to get acompany official to sign a document that she later altered toobtain promissory notes guaranteed by Nikko. Ms. Sun admittedusing that document and other false records to obtain loansfrom Dreieck, a Swiss financial institution, for ChineseInternational Growth Fund, a shell corporation controlled byMs. Sun and her unidentified co-conspirators.   The altered document could have allowed loans of as muchas $120 million. Dreieck funded a total of $36 million beforethe scheme was discovered, prosecutors said. Dreieck andTokyo-based Nikko cooperated in the government'sinvestigation.   Ms. Sun is scheduled to be sentenced Nov. 6 before JudgeLawrence McKenna in federal court in Manhattan. She faces apossible substantial prison sentence and a fine of as much as$1.5 million.</TEXT></DOC>